    <!-- FERS SUPPLEMENT -->
    <section id="supplement" class="fed-ed-fers-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER IV: THE BRIDGE</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-fers-section-title">FERS <em>Supplement</em> Strategy</h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fers-body">The FERS supplement bridges the income gap from retirement until you're eligible for Social Security at age 62. This benefit can provide $1,200-$2,000 per month, but it comes with specific eligibility requirements and income limitations.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">FERS Supplement Eligibility</h3>
        <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0;">
          <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6; font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b;">
            <strong style="color: #003870;">MRA + 30 years:</strong> Full supplement with no reduction
          </li>
          <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6; font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b;">
            <strong style="color: #003870;">Age 60 + 20 years:</strong> Full supplement with no reduction
          </li>
          <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b;">
            <strong style="color: #003870;">Annual Earnings Test:</strong> $1 reduction for every $2 over $23,400 (2025)
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fers-body">The supplement is subject to the Social Security earnings test — if you work after retirement and earn more than the annual limit, your supplement is reduced. This makes post-retirement employment planning crucial for supplement recipients.</p>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fers-body">Important: The FERS supplement automatically ends when you turn 62, regardless of when you actually claim Social Security. This creates a potential income gap that must be planned for in advance.</p>
    </section>
    
    <!-- SURVIVOR BENEFITS -->
    <section id="survivor" class="fed-ed-fers-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER V: PROTECTION</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-fers-section-title">Survivor <em>Benefits</em> Strategy</h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fers-body">Your FERS survivor benefit election is irrevocable and significantly impacts both your retirement income and your spouse's financial security. This decision requires careful analysis of your specific situation.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <table class="fed-ed-comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Survivor Benefit Option</th>
              <th>Cost to Retiree</th>
              <th>Survivor Receives</th>
              <th>Best For</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Full Survivor Benefit</strong></td>
              <td>10% reduction</td>
              <td>50% of annuity</td>
              <td>Spouse depends on pension income</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Partial Survivor Benefit</strong></td>
              <td>5% reduction</td>
              <td>25% of annuity</td>
              <td>Some spouse protection needed</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="highlight">
              <td><strong>No Survivor Benefit</strong></td>
              <td>No reduction</td>
              <td>Nothing</td>
              <td>Spouse has independent retirement</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fers-body">Many federal employees automatically choose the full survivor benefit without analyzing alternatives. Life insurance, spousal benefits, and other assets may provide better value than reducing your pension by 10% for life.</p>
    </section>
    
    <!-- MILITARY BUYBACK -->
    <section id="military" class="fed-ed-fers-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VI: SERVICE CREDIT</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-fers-section-title">Military <em>Buyback</em> Analysis</h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fers-body">Buying back military service credit can significantly increase your FERS annuity by adding years to your creditable service calculation. The decision requires a detailed cost-benefit analysis based on your specific situation.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-stats-grid">
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">3%</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">Base Military Pay Cost</span>
        </div>
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">$8,000</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">Example Buyback Cost</span>
        </div>
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">$140,000</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">Lifetime Pension Increase</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fers-body">From Mike's book: The military buyback example shows a federal employee who paid $8,000 to buy back 4 years of military service, which increased their annual pension by $2,400 and provided over $140,000 in additional lifetime benefits.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Key Considerations</h3>
        <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0;">
          <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6; font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b;">
            <strong style="color: #003870;">Payback Period:</strong> How long to recover the deposit cost
          </li>
          <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6; font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b;">
            <strong style="color: #003870;">Life Expectancy:</strong> Total lifetime value of increased benefits
          </li>
          <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6; font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b;">
            <strong style="color: #003870;">Interest Timing:</strong> Deposit within 3 years avoids interest charges
          </li>
          <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b;">
            <strong style="color: #003870;">Survivor Impact:</strong> Increased benefits for spouse if elected
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>
    
    <!-- OPTIMIZATION -->
    <section id="optimization" class="fed-ed-fers-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VII: OPTIMIZATION</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-fers-section-title">Maximizing Your <em>FERS</em> Benefits</h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fers-body">Optimizing your FERS benefits requires coordinating multiple moving pieces: retirement timing, high-3 salary management, sick leave conversion, and benefit elections. Small optimizations can result in significant lifetime value.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Optimization Strategies</h3>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 2rem;">
          <div>
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Timing Strategies</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6;">
              <li>Retirement date optimization</li>
              <li>High-3 salary timing</li>
              <li>Sick leave maximization</li>
              <li>Promotional timing analysis</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Benefit Coordination</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6;">
              <li>TSP withdrawal sequencing</li>
              <li>Social Security timing</li>
              <li>Tax minimization strategies</li>
              <li>Healthcare continuation planning</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-fers-body">Your FERS pension includes Cost of Living Adjustments (COLAs) that protect against inflation. The COLA formula provides full adjustments when inflation is 2% or less, caps adjustments at 2% when inflation is 2.1-3%, and provides inflation minus 1% when inflation exceeds 3%.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
</section>

<!-- FAQ SECTION -->
<section class="fed-ed-faq">
  <div class="fed-ed-faq-inner">
    <div>
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VIII: COMMON QUESTIONS</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-fers-section-title">FERS Planning <em>FAQ</em></h2>
      <p class="fed-ed-fers-body">Everything you need to know about FERS retirement and your federal pension planning.</p>
      <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
        <a href="/contact/" class="fed-ed-btn-primary">Schedule FERS Review</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="fed-ed-faq-accordion">
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">How is my FERS annuity calculated?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">Your FERS annuity is calculated using the formula: years of creditable service × high-3 average salary × multiplier. The standard multiplier is 1% for most employees. If you retire at age 62 or older with at least 20 years of service, the multiplier increases to 1.1%. Special category employees (law enforcement, firefighters, air traffic controllers) receive 1.7% for the first 20 years and 1% thereafter. Your high-3 is your highest average basic pay during any 3 consecutive years of service.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">What is the FERS supplement?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">The FERS supplement is a special benefit that approximates the Social Security benefit you earned while employed under FERS. It's designed to bridge the income gap from retirement until you're eligible for Social Security at age 62. You only receive the supplement if you retire at your Minimum Retirement Age (MRA) with 30 years of service, or at age 60 with 20 years. The supplement ends when you turn 62, regardless of when you claim Social Security.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">When can I retire under FERS?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">FERS offers several retirement options depending on your age and service. Immediate retirement is available at age 62 with 5 years of service, age 60 with 20 years, or at your MRA with 30 years. You can also retire at your MRA with 10-29 years, but you'll face a 5% per year reduction for each year under age 62. Your MRA depends on your birth year — it's age 56 for those born 1953-1964, and gradually increases to age 57 for those born 1970 or later.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">Should I buy back my military time?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">Buying back military service credit can increase your FERS annuity by adding years to your creditable service calculation. The cost is typically 3% of your military base pay, plus interest if you make the deposit after your first three years of federal civilian service. Whether it makes financial sense depends on your specific situation — how much service time you'd add, how close you are to retirement, and your life expectancy. We can calculate the exact payback period and lifetime value for your situation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">What happens to my pension if I leave early?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">If you leave federal service before meeting immediate retirement eligibility, you have options depending on your years of service. With at least 5 years of FERS coverage, you can leave your contributions in the system and receive a deferred retirement benefit starting at age 62. With 10 or more years, you can begin receiving benefits at your MRA, though with a reduction if you're under 62. Alternatively, you can request a refund of your FERS contributions, but this means forfeiting your future annuity and the government's contributions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<script>
(function() {
  document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-faq-trigger').forEach(function(btn) {
    btn.addEventListener('click', function() {
      var item = this.closest('.fed-ed-faq-item');
      var isOpen = item.classList.contains('active');
      
      // Close all items
      document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-faq-item').forEach(function(el) {
        el.classList.remove('active');
      });
      
      // Open clicked item if it wasn't already open
      if (!isOpen) {
        item.classList.add('active');
      }
    });
  });
  
  // Smooth scroll for navigation links
  document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-fers-nav a').forEach(function(link) {
    link.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
      e.preventDefault();
      const targetId = this.getAttribute('href');
      const targetElement = document.querySelector(targetId);
      if (targetElement) {
        targetElement.scrollIntoView({
          behavior: 'smooth',
          block: 'start'
        });
      }
    });
  });
})();
</script>